Methodology for Identifying Unhealthy Tables in Snowflake
Hi Team,
As part of the Snowflake validation, I evaluated table health using Snowflake’s clustering metadata.
Approach used:
Used the SYSTEM$CLUSTERING_INFORMATION() function to retrieve clustering metrics for each table.
The clustering column used for analysis was selected based on table type:
Streaming tables → kafka_process_dt
Other tables → ods_business_day
These columns were identified from the earlier column inventory extracted from Cloudera.
Metrics analyzed from clustering metadata:
total_partition_count
constant_partition_count
average_depth
average_overlaps
Criteria used to classify table health:
A table was marked Unhealthy if any of the following conditions were met:
average_depth > 5
average_overlaps > 5
constant_partition_ratio < 0.5
(where constant_partition_ratio = constant_partition_count / total_partition_count)
Tables not meeting these conditions were classified as Healthy.
These thresholds were used to identify tables where micro-partition pruning may be inefficient due to high partition overlap or deeper clustering depth.
A report listing the tables identified as unhealthy has been generated for further review.
Please let me know if any additional details are required.
